site.description: Next to burnt patch and direct seeding, narrow linear strip, approximately 10m wide, running parallell to fence line adjoining park with playground. 2 50m transects undertaken. Patch situated within  large, poor quality grassland dominated by Avena sp. and Nasella sp..
Evidence of burning, 50m from railway tracks, lots of forbs obvious to naked eye. Dry cracking soil. Some obvious weeds. Pete impromptu meeting: Railway, higher quality but older burn.

site.description: Very weedy, Avena, 3 * burn patches that were inked together. Housing on all other 3 sides. Part of a network of grasslands connected via creek.

Obvious geraniums and bluebells in intertussock spaces.

site.description: Cracking soils, very rocky. Slope from north east corner down to southwest corner of eastern patch. Stellaria pungeons vs. asperula - saw both but called it asperula this was with Finley.

Rocks removed? Presences of dry stone wall parralell to to creek. Senecio - large adults to 1m and (reeemitinace?) Industry, trucks, air pollution, patchy burn? Large avena clumps. Obvious convolvulous patches. North block burnt in weeks preceeding surveys - that patch not surveyed. Patch surveyed was burnt in 2013.

Undulating site. Slight slope to creek. Surrounded by industry along fenced edge. Cooper street to northern edge. Derocking along firebreaks being undertaken. Herbivory. especially of danthonias. Similar soil to Jukes Rd and Emma street.

fiona_notes: No apparent mgmt, heavy kangaroo grazing
site.description: Hiked for 1.5 hours through burn, loads of kangaroos (approx. 30) evidence of strong grazing. Transect on hill blue devil and convolvulous sighted, Acaena lillies and tricoryne. On top of stony rise pocked with small depressions, with sedge and moisture-loving plants such as isolepis, juncus sp. and dichondra repens.
